content.description:
Easy corner left of the arete (Kornered) 

 #67 in the MN/WI book.
content.protection: Anchors at top off east side of platform. Sketchy setup left and well below the overlook. Use lots of webbing to set low enough. Do not anchor to the overlook platform.
content.location: The obvious corner over the east side of the overlook. Set anchors and rap down.

content.description:
Fun short arete just right of the corner (Minihedral).   Watch the swing if you've set anchors too far left. 

 #66 in MN/WI book.
content.protection: Anchors at top off east side of platform. Sketchy setup left and well below the overlook. Use lots of webbing to set low enough. Do not anchor to the overlook platform.
content.location: Farthest right route facing the wall. Set anchors and rap down.

content.description:
Tough mantle move over the low roof and straight up the face left of the corner.  

#68 in MN/WI book.
content.protection: Anchors at top off east side of platform. Sketchy setup left and well below the overlook. Use lots of webbing to set low enough. Do not anchor to the overlook platform.
content.location: The face climb that starts under the low roof beside the corner. Set anchors and rap down.

content.description:
Start in the crack left of the roof just in front of the tree. Traverse left and smear up the finger crack in the middle without Peter Panning and then straight up the rest of the crack. Make it much harder by trying to mantle up the awkward boulders and make your way up to the face climb left of the start into the crack. 

#69 in the MN/WI book.
content.protection: Anchors at top. Set and rap down.
content.location: The only climb off the west (right) side of the overlook. Anchors are easy to set here, but don't use the platform itself. There is a good tree to use, but be careful of its branches.

content.description: Short, relatively easy climbs. Nothing terribly amazing, but when it's hot and the strip is full, the shaded belays at the base are definitely nice. Standard top rope routes from both sides of the overlook platform. However, don't use the platform itself for pro. Be careful of thoughtless tourists throwing trash over and gawking at you climbing. And also be wary of leaving your gear on top and of your anchor placements, especially webbing.
